Effective Dynamical Supersymmetry: A brief discussion 

A phenomenological manifestation of octonionic structure (based on Cayley numbers) has been found in connection with quark dynamics inside hadrons leading to an effective dynamical supersymmetry. It is based on  supergroups yielding combined classification of mesons and baryons. Under the color group ,  and  states transform as

 

Under the spin-flavor group , they transform as 66135, and 661521, respectively. Now, mesons are  states while baryons are  states. If one writes  as , where  is a diquark, , the quantum numbers of  are: for color, 3, since when combined with  must give a color singlet; for spin flavor, 21, since when combined with color must give antisymmetric wave functions. But the quantum numbers of  for color is 3, and for spin-flavor, 6. Thus  and  have the same color quantum numbers (color forces can not distinguish between  and ). Therefore there is an approximate dynamic supersymmetry in hadrons with supersymmetric partners

 
            
All hadrons can be obtained by combining  and : mesons are , baryons are , antibaryons are  and exotic mesons are . Since the dimensions of the internal degrees of freedom of  quarks is , and of diquarks for , 18 and for  is , then the corresponding supersymmetry is .

In a way similar to that used in the construction of mass formulas for  and  one can also construct mass formulas for  that describe simultaneously mesons and baryons. Important consequences of these formulas are: (i) slopes of mesonic and baryonic trajectories are identical; (ii) masses of some particles satisfy particular relations, for example , described by semirelativistic and relativistic formulations. Both of these are experimentally verified.  supersymmetry also naturally leads to the existence of  states. There are now several indications that  and  mesons are quark-antidiquark states. Review of this model and recent experimental situation is discussed in detail in Gursey and Tze, Anselmino, et al, and Klempt.


It is worth noting that  and  behave like fermionic annihilation and creation operators:
, , and . This fermionic Heisenberg algebra shows the three split units  to be Grassmann numbers. Being non-associative, these split units give rise to an exceptional Grassmann algebra. Thus this algebra allows: triplettriplet=antitriplet, and tripletantitriplet=singlet. Now the multiplication rules for color is given in Eq.(). But 8 is not allowed if we want color singlet mesons, and 6 is not allowed if we want to have color singlet baryons. Thus the multiplication rules of quarks and antiquarks are identical to those of split octonions. Therefore associating quark fields with split octonion units  by choosing uq, and antiquarks by uq, an effective supersymmetric model is constructed based on octonions where all the unwanted states are automatically  suppressed by means of this algebra. This model gave the first application in particle physics of dynamic (internal) supersymmetries. For a brief history of dynamic symmetries we refer to an article by Franco Iachello, and for an extensive review of octonions to John Baez's comprehensive article.

Octonions and Exceptional Hilbert Spaces 

        In recent years a careful study of the symmetries of the directly 
observed hadronic world and strong interactions led us to the colored quark 
substructure. Also, the properties of weak and 
electromagnetic interactions help us to unveil a deep symmetry between 
the directly observed leptons and the partly observable quarks. These 
fermions seem to be represented by local fields that belong to multiplets 
of a single unifying group  that is valid locally. What distinguishes this group ?  What is so basic about the exact color group? In trying to answer these questions we move to the next sphere of abstraction and see if the unification of strong, electromagnetic and weak interactions points to the geometrical properties of a deeper Hilbert space structure.
         
         During the ebullient first decade after the birth of Quantum 
Mechanics, the grand masters of the period explored all the possibilities 
for the extension of Quantum Mechanical concepts and methods. In 1933 
Jordan  suggested a new formulation of Quantum Mechanics based on 
what became to be known as Jordan algebras. In the standard formulation, 
states are represented by vectors (kets) in a Hilbert space, while observables 
are represented by Hermitian matrices acting on the states. In the Jordan 
formulation an algebra of observables is defined so that observables can be 
combined to give other observables. For instance, in classical mechanics if 
 and  are observables, so are  ,  and . If  and 
 are replaced by hermitian matrices  and , the only the combination

 
is a hermitian matrix, hence an observable representing the classical . 
The symmetrized product Eq.() is the Jordan product of  and . 
Unlike ordinary matrix multiplication which is noncommutative but associative, the 
Jordan product is commutative but not associative. The associator

 
is antisymmetrical in  and  and satisfies the Jordan identity

 
which makes the algebra of observables power associative so that
 is an unambiguous expression that represents the classical observable 
.
         
