         The Desargues property can now be rephrased in Quantum Mechanical
language as follows.
         
         Geometrically we have a point  and 3 points , ,  not on a line. 
Take a point  on the line , a point  on the line  and a point  on 
the line  such that , ,  do not lie on a line. Now the lines  and 
 intersect at a point . Similarly  and  intersect at  and  
and  intersect at . The geometry is Desarguesian if ,  and  lie 
on the same line. The Desargues property holds in a projective geometry if 
the projective plane has dimension . In 2 dimensions it holds if the 
coordinates of the point are real, complex or quaternionic, i.e. if they 
belong to an associative algebra. On the other hand in the Moufang plane, 
the coordinates of a point are octonionic. Because of the non-associativity 
of octonions, there exist non-Desarguesian configurations.
         
         In Quantum Mechanics we take states corresponding to the points , 
, , . We superpose  and  to obtain  and proceed similarly for  and .
 We now construct a state  which is simultaneously a superposition of states 
,  and also or states , . We construct states  and  in the same way. 
If the states , ,  are linearly related we have the Desargues property. 
If not, we say that we have a non-Desarguesian Quantum Mechanics. It follows 
that the octonionic Quantum Mechanics of Jordan, Wigner and von Neumann is 
non-Desarguesian. It represents a completely new kind of Quantum Mechanics 
in a finite dimensional Hilbert space in which the superposition principle 
is modified for states corresponding to non-associative triples.


